{"id":"1901.06891","submitter":"Thomas Karg","authors":"Thomas M. Karg, Baptiste Gouraud, Klemens Hammerer, Philipp Treutlein","title":"Remote Hamiltonian Interactions Mediated by Light","comments":"18 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 99, 063829 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.99.063829","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We address a fundamental question of quantum optics: Can a beam of light\nmediate coherent Hamiltonian interactions between two distant quantum systems?\nThis is an intriguing question whose answer is not a priori clear, since the\nlight carries away information about the systems and might be subject to\nlosses, giving rise to intrinsic decoherence channels associated with the\ncoupling. Our answer is affirmative and we derive a particularly simple\nsufficient condition for the interactions to be Hamiltonian: The light field\nneeds to interact twice with the systems and the second interaction has to be\nthe time reversal of the first. We demonstrate that, even in the presence of\nsignificant optical loss, coherent interactions can be realized and generate\nsubstantial amounts of entanglement between the systems. Our method is directly\napplicable for building hybrid quantum systems, with relevant applications in\nthe fields of optomechanics and atomic ensembles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Jan 2019 11:48:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 27 Aug 2019 12:39:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-28"}
